Bring a medium #pot{} of salted water to a boil. Wash and dry @scallions{2}, then trim and thinly slice, separating greens and whites.

Once water boils, add @cavatappi pasta{6%oz} to pot. Cook until al dente, ~{8-10%minutes}. Scoop out and reserve ½ cup pasta cooking water, then drain.

Meanwhile, tear @pulled pork{10%oz} into smaller, bite-sized pieces. Heat a large drizzle of @vegetable oil{2%tsp} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add pork and a large pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, stirring a few times, until pork begins to brown, ~{4-5%minutes}. Stir in scallion whites and cook ~{30%seconds}. Transfer to a #plate{}.

After draining cavatappi, lower heat under pan used for pork to medium and add @butter{2%tbsp}. Once melted, stir in @flour{1%tbsp} and cook ~{30%seconds}. Slowly whisk in @milk{6.75%oz}, reserved pasta cooking water, @sweet and smoky BBQ seasoning{1%tbsp}, and a few pinches of salt and pepper. Bring to a simmer, then let bubble until just thickened, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Remove pan from heat and add @cream cheese{2%oz} and @Mexican cheese blend{½%cup}, stirring until smooth. Stir in cavatappi and pork to combine. Season with salt and pepper.

Divide pasta between plates. Garnish with scallion greens and @hot sauce{1%tsp}.

> This is an ultimate take on your favorite comfort foods, combining pasta nirvana with melt-in-your-mouth pulled pork and smoky barbecue spices.